        <div id="options" class="panel">
            <div class="panel-title">Options & Pathways</div>
            <div class="panel-subtitle">The different routes available and what each involves</div>

            <div class="section-heading">
                <span class="icon icon-gold">🔀</span> Divorce Process Options
            </div>

            <div class="option-grid">
                <div class="option-card recommended">
                    <div class="option-name">Solicitor Negotiation</div>
                    <div class="option-desc">Each party instructs their own solicitor. Negotiations happen through solicitors to reach a <strong>Consent Order</strong> approved by the court.</div>
                    <div class="pros-cons">
                        <div class="pro">Professional guidance throughout</div>
                        <div class="pro">Avoids court confrontation</div>
                        <div class="pro">Legally binding outcome</div>
                        <div class="con">Legal costs (typically £5,000–£15,000)</div>
                        <div class="con">Requires his willingness to engage</div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="option-card">
                    <div class="option-name">Mediation</div>
                    <div class="option-desc">A neutral mediator helps both parties reach agreement. Required to attend a <strong>MIAM</strong> (Mediation Information & Assessment Meeting) before court in most cases.</div>
                    <div class="pros-cons">
                        <div class="pro">Lower cost (£500–£2,000)</div>
                        <div class="pro">Faster if cooperative</div>
                        <div class="pro">Less adversarial</div>
                        <div class="con">Not binding until formalised</div>
                        <div class="con">Less protection if power imbalance</div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="option-card">
                    <div class="option-name">Court Application (Financial)</div>
                    <div class="option-desc">If agreement cannot be reached, either party can apply to court for a <strong>Financial Remedy Order</strong>. The judge decides how assets are divided.</div>
                    <div class="pros-cons">
                        <div class="pro">Judge makes binding decision</div>
                        <div class="pro">Full financial disclosure forced</div>
                        <div class="con">Expensive (£15,000–£30,000+)</div>
                        <div class="con">Slow (12–24 months)</div>
                        <div class="con">Emotionally difficult</div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="option-card">
                    <div class="option-name">Collaborative Law</div>
                    <div class="option-desc">Both parties and their solicitors commit to resolving everything outside court. If it fails, new solicitors must be instructed.</div>
                    <div class="pros-cons">
                        <div class="pro">Dignified, structured process</div>
                        <div class="pro">Four-way meetings</div>
                        <div class="con">If fails, costs increase significantly</div>
                        <div class="con">Requires genuine cooperation</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="section-heading">
                <span class="icon icon-sage">🏠</span> Property Outcome Options
            </div>

            <div class="accordion-item">
                <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
                    Option A: Transfer of Property to Saima
                    <span class="accordion-arrow">▼</span>
                </div>
                <div class="accordion-body">
                    <div class="accordion-body-inner">
                        The house is transferred solely into your name. This may require taking over the mortgage or refinancing. <strong>Most favourable outcome</strong> — provides long-term stability. Realistic if the equity split and mortgage affordability can be structured, potentially with a compensating lump sum paid over time or offset against other assets (e.g., pension).
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="accordion-item">
                <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
                    Option B: Mesher Order (Deferred Sale)
                    <span class="accordion-arrow">▼</span>
                </div>
                <div class="accordion-body">
                    <div class="accordion-body-inner">
                        Property remains in joint names. Saima and children stay in the home. Sale is deferred until a <strong>trigger event</strong> — typically the youngest child turning 18 (2035), Saima remarrying, or voluntary agreement. At that point, equity is divided according to an agreed split. <strong>Very common outcome</strong> in cases with dependent children.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="accordion-item">
                <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
                    Option C: Sale and Division
                    <span class="accordion-arrow">▼</span>
                </div>
                <div class="accordion-body">
                    <div class="accordion-body-inner">
                        Property is sold and equity divided. Less desirable given the children's need for housing stability and Saima's health, but the split can be adjusted in her favour (e.g., 60/40 or 65/35) to reflect needs. A court would be <strong>reluctant</strong> to order this while she is undergoing treatment with three school-age children.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="accordion-item">
                <div class="accordion-header" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
                    Option D: Martin Order (Sale on Specific Events)
                    <span class="accordion-arrow">▼</span>
                </div>
                <div class="accordion-body">
                    <div class="accordion-body-inner">
                        Similar to a Mesher Order but the trigger is not tied to the children's ages — it might be triggered by Saima cohabiting with a new partner or by her death. Less common, but used when children are older or the primary concern is the spouse's housing needs rather than child-specific factors.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

