        <!-- PANEL 4: PROPERTY & FINANCE -->
        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <div id="property" class="panel">
            <div class="panel-title">Property & Finances</div>
            <div class="panel-subtitle">Building the financial picture and protecting your contributions</div>

            <div class="section-heading">
                <span class="icon icon-gold">📑</span> Financial Disclosure — What You Need
            </div>

            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">Form E — The Full Financial Statement</div>
                <p>In contested proceedings, both parties must complete <strong>Form E</strong> — a comprehensive financial disclosure including all assets, income, debts, and expenses. Even if you settle through solicitor negotiation, a full financial picture is essential. This covers:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Property valuations</li>
                    <li>Mortgage details and statements</li>
                    <li>Bank accounts and savings</li>
                    <li>Pensions</li>
                    <li>Income (employment, self-employment, benefits)</li>
                    <li>Debts and liabilities</li>
                    <li>Businesses or investments</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="section-heading">
                <span class="icon icon-sage">🏠</span> Documenting Your Contributions
            </div>

            <div class="card highlight highlight-sage">
                <div class="card-header">Evidence to Gather — Your Financial Input</div>
                <p>While the court looks at "needs" first, clear evidence of your contributions strengthens your negotiating position significantly:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Deposit proof:</strong> Bank transfer records, solicitor completion statements</li>
                    <li><strong>Extension funding:</strong> Receipts, invoices, bank statements showing payments to builders/contractors</li>
                    <li><strong>Kitchen costs:</strong> Purchase receipts, credit card or bank statements</li>
                    <li><strong>Legal fees:</strong> Solicitor invoices and payment records</li>
                    <li><strong>Any messages/texts</strong> confirming your financial input or agreements about money</li>
                    <li><strong>Before and after valuations</strong> if available (showing value increase from your investment)</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="section-heading">
                <span class="icon icon-rose">⚠️</span> His Remortgaging — What It Means
            </div>

            <div class="card highlight highlight-rose">
                <div class="card-header">Important Context</div>
                <p>Remortgaging during the marriage to fund family home improvements is treated as use of a <strong>matrimonial asset for joint benefit</strong>. It does not give him a superior claim. Points to investigate:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>How many times was the property remortgaged?</li>
                    <li>What was the money used for? (Home improvements vs personal spending)</li>
                    <li>What is the current outstanding mortgage balance?</li>
                    <li>Has the increased borrowing reduced the equity available to both parties?</li>
                    <li>Were you consulted and did you consent to the remortgages?</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top: 0.8rem;">If remortgage funds were used for anything other than the family's benefit, this can be raised as <strong>financial misconduct</strong> in proceedings.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="section-heading">
                <span class="icon icon-blue">💷</span> Child Maintenance Calculation
            </div>

            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">CMS Standard Rates (3 Children, Primary Carer)</div>
                <p>Child maintenance is calculated by the <strong>Child Maintenance Service</strong> using his gross weekly income:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Gross weekly income up to £200:</strong> Nil rate or flat rate (£7/week)</li>
                    <li><strong>£200–£800/week:</strong> Reduced rate</li>
                    <li><strong>£800–£3,000/week:</strong> 19% for 3 children</li>
                    <li>Adjustments for shared care nights</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top: 0.8rem;">This is a <strong>separate system</strong> from the divorce financial settlement and can be applied for independently at any time through the CMS.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

