        <!-- PANEL 5: CHILDREN -->
        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <div id="children" class="panel">
            <div class="panel-title">Children</div>
            <div class="panel-subtitle">How the law protects the children's welfare and stability</div>

            <div class="card highlight highlight-gold">
                <div class="card-header">🛡️ First Principle: Children's Welfare Comes First</div>
                <p>Under both the <strong>Matrimonial Causes Act 1973</strong> (finances) and the <strong>Children Act 1989</strong> (residence and contact), the welfare of the children is the court's <strong>paramount consideration</strong>. This is the single most important factor in every decision.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="section-heading">
                <span class="icon icon-sage">🏠</span> Where Will the Children Live?
            </div>

            <div class="card">
                <p>Since the children (14, 13, 9) currently live primarily with Saima and she is their primary carer, the strong presumption is they will <strong>continue to live with her</strong>. The court considers:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Status quo:</strong> Courts are reluctant to disrupt children's established living arrangements</li>
                    <li><strong>Ages:</strong> At 14 and 13, the older children's own wishes carry significant weight</li>
                    <li><strong>Primary attachment:</strong> Saima as the primary day-to-day carer</li>
                    <li><strong>Schooling:</strong> Stability of school arrangements</li>
                    <li><strong>Medical context:</strong> The children need stability during their mother's treatment</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="section-heading">
                <span class="icon icon-blue">👨‍👧‍👦</span> Contact Arrangements
            </div>

            <div class="card">
                <p>The court starts from a <strong>presumption of parental involvement</strong> — both parents should have a meaningful relationship with the children unless there is a safeguarding concern. Typical arrangements might include:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Alternate weekends</li>
                    <li>One midweek evening</li>
                    <li>Shared school holidays</li>
                    <li>Flexibility around the children's activities and preferences</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top: 0.8rem;">The children's own views become increasingly important as they grow older — particularly the 14-year-old, whose wishes are given considerable weight.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="section-heading">
                <span class="icon icon-rose">📝</span> What to Document About the Children
            </div>

            <div class="card highlight highlight-rose">
                <ul>
                    <li>School details and attendance records</li>
                    <li>Who manages school communications, homework, activities</li>
                    <li>Medical appointments — who books and attends</li>
                    <li>Daily routines — who does school runs, meals, bedtime</li>
                    <li>Any messages showing your primary role in caring for them</li>
                    <li>Impact of your treatment on care arrangements and who assists</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

