        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <div id="health" class="panel">
            <div class="panel-title">Health as a Legal Factor</div>
            <div class="panel-subtitle">How your medical situation is recognised by the court</div>

            <div class="card highlight highlight-rose">
                <div class="card-header">🏥 Current Medical Status</div>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Diagnosis:</strong> Grade 3 invasive ductal carcinoma, Triple Negative (ER−, PR−, HER2−)</li>
                    <li><strong>Stage:</strong> T2N1M0 (Stage IIb), multifocal across three quadrants</li>
                    <li><strong>Treatment:</strong> Currently mid-way through neoadjuvant chemotherapy + immunotherapy</li>
                    <li><strong>Awaiting:</strong> Mastectomy date following completion of systemic therapy</li>
                    <li><strong>Further treatment expected:</strong> Post-mastectomy radiotherapy, possible targeted adjuvant therapy</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="section-heading">
                <span class="icon icon-gold">⚖️</span> Legal Relevance Under Section 25
            </div>

            <div class="card">
                <div class="card-header">Health is an explicit statutory factor</div>
                <p>The court is <strong>required by law</strong> to consider the health of both parties when deciding financial outcomes. Active cancer treatment impacts the court's assessment in multiple ways:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Reduced earning capacity:</strong> During and potentially after treatment, ability to work is significantly limited</li>
                    <li><strong>Increased housing needs:</strong> A medically vulnerable primary carer needs stable, secure accommodation</li>
                    <li><strong>Future uncertainty:</strong> Ongoing treatment, recovery, surveillance all affect long-term planning</li>
                    <li><strong>Care dependency:</strong> During treatment, the carer needs support — she should not be destabilised</li>
                    <li><strong>Children's welfare intersection:</strong> Disrupting the primary carer's housing during treatment directly harms children's welfare</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="section-heading">
                <span class="icon icon-sage">📄</span> Medical Evidence to Retain
            </div>

            <div class="card highlight highlight-sage">
                <div class="card-header">Documents to Collect and Keep Safe</div>
                <ul>
                    <li>Original referral letter (2-week wait suspected cancer pathway)</li>
                    <li>Diagnostic biopsy and pathology reports</li>
                    <li>MRI and CT scan reports</li>
                    <li>Oncology treatment plan letter</li>
                    <li>Chemotherapy appointment schedule</li>
                    <li>Any correspondence confirming treatment impact (fatigue, fitness to work)</li>
                    <li>Surgeon's letter regarding planned mastectomy</li>
                    <li>Letters from GP confirming ongoing treatment and reduced capacity</li>
                    <li>Immunotherapy and radiotherapy plans when available</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top: 0.8rem;"><strong>Tip:</strong> Request a <strong>formal letter from your consultant oncologist</strong> summarising your diagnosis, treatment plan, and expected timeline. This becomes powerful evidence in financial proceedings.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="section-heading">
                <span class="icon icon-blue">⏰</span> Timing & Health
            </div>

            <div class="card">
                <p>The stage at which proceedings are initiated affects how strongly the health factor weighs:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>During active treatment</strong> (current) → Strongest position. Court will be very protective.</li>
                    <li><strong>Immediately post-surgery, during recovery</strong> → Still strong. Recovery and ongoing treatment are clear factors.</li>
                    <li><strong>After full recovery, returned to work</strong> → Health factor diminishes as a current need, though long-term implications remain relevant.</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top: 0.8rem;">This is not about strategic timing for advantage — it is about ensuring the court has the full picture of your circumstances <strong>at the point decisions are made</strong>.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

